SIMPLE: paunch
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Paunch
<hw>Paunch</hw> <pr>(p⟦add⟧nch <it>or</it> p⟦aum⟧nch; 277)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>panch</ets>, <ets>pance</ets>, F.
<ets>panse</ets>, L. <ets>pantex</ets>, <ets>panticis</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The belly and its contents; the
abdomen; also, the first stomach, or rumen, of ruminants. See
<er>Rumen</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A paunch mat; -- called also
<altname>panch</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The thickened rim of a bell, struck by the
clapper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A noticeably protruding belly; a potbelly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Paunch mat</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a thick mat
made of strands of rope, used to prevent the yard or rigging from
chafing.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Paunch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Paunch
<hw>Paunch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Paunched</conjf> <pr>(p⟦add⟧ncht <it>or</it> p⟦aum⟧ncht)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Paunching</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To pierce or rip the belly of; to eviscerate; to
disembowel.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To stuff with food.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Udall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Paunchy</ent>⟦br⟧
